entry.title: Flash Flood Warning issued February 11 at 8:36PM EST until February 12 at 1:15AM EST by NWS Peachtree City GA
entry.summary:
At 836 PM EST, Radar and automated rain gages estimate between 2 and 4 inches of rain have fallen since 5 PM. Flash flooding from creeks coming out of their banks has been reported in parts of north Columbus. Even though the heavy rain has tapered off, creek and rivers will continue to rise. Additional rainfall amounts up to 1 inch is also possible in the warned area through 1 AM. Flash flooding is ongoing or expected to begin shortly.
HAZARD...Flash flooding caused by thunderstorms.
SOURCE...Public reported.
IMPACT...Flash flooding of small creeks and streams, urban areas, highways, streets and underpasses as well as other poor drainage and low-lying areas.
Some locations that will experience flash flooding include... Columbus, Bibb City, Upatoi, Flat Rock, Kenwood, Columbus Metropolitan Airport, Edgewood, Midland, Vista Terrace, Fortson, Highland Park, Laurel Hills, Saint Marys Hills, Rose Hill, Green Island Hills, Avondale, Benning Park, Benning Hills, Carter Acres and Goat Rock Lake.
This includes the following streams and drainages... Boyd Branch, Dozier Creek, Heiferhorn Creek, Riley Branch, Randall Creek, Flatrock Branch, Kendall Creek, Cooper Creek, Chattahoochee River, Lindsey Creek, Upatoi Creek, Standing Boy Creek, Bull Creek, Wolf Creek, Steam Mill Creek, Flatrock Creek, Baker Creek and Tiger Creek.

entry.title: Special Weather Statement issued February 11 at 2:45PM AKST by NWS Fairbanks AK
entry.summary:
A strong low pressure system will move into Bristol Bay during the day on Monday. This system will bring a large amount of warm and moist air over Western Alaska starting Monday into Tuesday. There is still a good deal of uncertainty on the strength and track of the system, but areas from Unalakleet south have a chance of freezing rain beginning Monday afternoon, with a chance of freezing rain spreading north to Kotzebue by Tuesday afternoon. Significant ice accumulations are possible and will be monitored as the event gets closer and details become more clear.
This storm could also bring heavy snow to the east side of the Nulato Hills, the the Southern Seward Peninsula, and to areas north of the Kobuk River. There could be brief blizzard conditions along the West Coast as well.
The system will also bring strong southeast winds gusting as high as 50 mph to the West Coast and to hills near the coast from Monday afternoon through Tuesday night. This will cause sea levels to rise 1 to 2 feet south of the Bering Strait on Tuesday and Wednesday. While flooding of infrastructure is not expected, these strong winds may cause water to be pushed on top of the sea ice making travel difficult.
Residents should stay tuned to the latest forecast updates at www.weather.gov/afg and prepare for a stormy start to the week.
